really? Leak detectors were added in 2023.1 release. 

the webinar says they can describe leak detectors and their state at 15:42 https://youtu.be/UKaLVR3HGSY?feature=shared

They have defined a custom state schema per webinar. They didn't provide a message to say they had detected a leak?

would this be any different from a state change event for `DetectorState`

https://github.com/DMTF/Redfish-Publications/blob/bff927ee3cd16e0c059845fba976bf738b0717b2/mockups/public-cooling-unit/ThermalEquipment/CDUs/1/LeakDetection/LeakDetectors/Moisture/index.json#L10
   

did you ask the redfish forum for advice?

> would this be any different from a state change event for DetectorState

This event is for asynchronous events generated by BMC https://github.com/openbmc/docs/blob/master/designs/event-logging.md
https://www.dmtf.org/sites/default/files/standards/documents/DSP2065_2024.1.pdf


> did you ask the redfish forum for advice?

Yes, i discussed with the Redfish forum and they don't have this defined yet - https://redfishforum.com/thread/1074/redfish-message-registry-leakdetection

can we get this link in the commit instead of buried in the comments?

preferably we'd have a pending discussion attribute (which is probably it's own patch to phosphor dbus interfaces) but at least in the change log to have a chance to find it with find with `git blame `.

> > would this be any different from a state change event for DetectorState

> This event is for asynchronous events generated by BMC

I was wondering if these should map to any of 
`ResourceChanged`, `ResourceStateChanged`, `ResourceStatusChangedCritical`, or `ResourceStatusChangedOK` from the base registry (from the DSP2065_2024.1 reference)

however it makes sense to expose this new state uniquely on our internal dbua before mapping in bmcweb, where it can change when Redfish catches up.  I guess we could emit both these and a specific OEM event (another forum topic the event subscription is supposed to allow non existent messages for forward compatibly but a client would not know if a more specific event was added and is implemented for these).

> can we get this link in the commit instead of buried in the comments?

Sure will add.

> I was wondering if these should map to any of
ResourceChanged, ResourceStateChanged, ResourceStatusChangedCritical, or ResourceStatusChangedOK from the base registry (from the DSP2065_2024.1 reference)

> however it makes sense to expose this new state uniquely on our internal dbua before mapping in bmcweb, where it can change when Redfish catches up. I guess we could emit both these and a specific OEM event (another forum topic the event subscription is supposed to allow non existent messages for forward compatibly but a client would not know if a more specific event was added and is implemented for these).

Refer to redfish-mapping attribute in design https://github.com/openbmc/docs/blob/master/designs/event-logging.md. My understanding is that the events which won't have this attribute defined will be specific to openBMC namespace. @Patrick can provide more details as he is implementing this feature in BMCWeb.

I see lots of design for converting to a Redfish Message Refistry but didn't see attribute after Redfish in that document.


I don't think the question about should we generate standard events and an OEM was addressed but agree it's not really germane to adding this interface, more suggesting the question be considered by Redfish or as a quality of implementation topic for bmcweb.

> I see lots of design for converting to a Redfish Message Refistry but didn't see attribute after Redfish in that document.
> 

redfish-mapping is the attribute name.

> 
> I don't think the question about should we generate standard events and an OEM was addressed but agree it's not really germane to adding this interface, more suggesting the question be considered by Redfish or as a quality of implementation topic for bmcweb.

The description of redfish-mapping explains details on this.
Resolving this comment as its related to EventLog design and not this specific PR. Milton you can start a thread on discord in case there are specific questions related to the design.
please add the link as described below

Redfish has now implemented a series of messages to clearly indicate when a previous indicator is no longer active.

should we include one now?

> Redfish has now implemented a series of messages to clearly indicate when a previous indicator is no longer active.

> should we include one now?

Refer to https://github.com/openbmc/docs/blob/master/designs/event-logging.md. It mentions how an active event will be marked resolved.
